Eurozone inflation rose in December, boosted primarily by higher energy costs, official data showed on Tuesday. According to a flash estimate from Eurostat, the European Union’s statistics office, annual inflation in December is expected to be 1.3%, up from 1.0% in November and in line with consensus. Food, alcohol, and tobacco recorded the highest annual rate, at 2.0% compared to 1.9% in November. But there was also a notable recovery in energy, ahead 0.2% compared to a 3.2% collapse in November, as oil prices improved. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network Claus Vistesen, the chief eurozone economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics, said: “This jump is consistent with the shift in base effects from last year’s collapse in oil prices, and won’t surprise anyone. “The key story, though, is that the energy CPI rate still looks too subdued compared to the trend in oil prices, not least given the recent increase on the back of rising geopolitical risks.